sections.Attitudes towards the smallfolk:
The exiled [[Viserys Targaryen]] was convinced that the smallfolk of [[Westeros]] were chafing under the usurper [[Robert Baratheon]]'s rule, and secretly hoping for the return of their true king Viserys.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[Winter is Coming]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt; Ser [[Jorah Mormont]] explains to [[Daenerys Targaryen]] that this is mere fantasy - particularly given that Robert's rule has been reasonably stable for the past seventeen years. Ultimately, Jorah says, the smallfolk care nothing about the political games being played by the high lords, so long as they don't directly affect them.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[Cripples, Bastards and Broken Things]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

[[Cersei Lannister]] drunkenly explains to [[Sansa Stark]] that her conception of ruling is that &quot;the only way to keep the smallfolk loyal is to make certain they fear you more than they do the enemy&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[Blackwater]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

When [[Tyrion Lannister]] arrives in [[King's Landing]] as acting [[Hand of the King]], he warns Cersei that the city is overburdened with refugees, and due to the war half of the city will be starving when winter comes. In this volatile environment, he criticizes the [[Massacre in King's Landing|purge]] of King Robert's [[Bastardy|bastard]] children, saying it has made her appear brutal and given the commoners a rallying cry against her. Cersei bluntly states that she does not care what &quot;the people&quot; think.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[The Night Lands]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt; [[Janos Slynt]] also tried to warn Cersei about the influx of starving refugees and strain on the city's resources, but she brushed off his concerns by telling him to simply bar the city's gates against the masses of refugees trying to seek shelter inside.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[The North Remembers]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt; As conditions worsen, when the royal party moves through the city after sending Princess [[Myrcella Baratheon|Myrcella]] off to [[Dorne]], a starving mob pelts Joffrey with insults and demands for bread, and ultimately, pelts him with cow dung. Joffrey brazenly shouts for his (heavily outnumbered) guards to kill them all, sparking off [[Riot of King's Landing|major food riots]] in which the royal party narrowly avoids being lynched by the mob. The fat and corrupt [[High Septon (Before the riot of King's Landing)|High Septon]] is torn limb from limb by the mob.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[The Old Gods and the New]]&lt;/ref&gt;

By contrast, when members of [[House Tyrell]] arrive in King's Landing after they enter into an alliance with the Lannisters, they are more concerned about helping the starving poor of the capital city. [[Margaery Tyrell]] and her attendants give out bread and toys to an orphanage, to [[Joffrey Baratheon]]'s confusion. She chides Cersei that the poor are no different from the highborn if given a chance.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[Valar Dohaeris]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt; Cersei later attempts to warn Joffrey about the Tyrells, accurately surmising that Margaery is making a great show of charity to the city's poor in order to build up support for herself, taking it away from the Lannisters in the process.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[Dark Wings, Dark Words]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

Tyrion later speaks with Margaery's grandmother [[Olenna Tyrell]], who insists that an expensive royal wedding will be a good distraction for the common people. Olenna tacitly acknowledges to Tyrion that the Tyrells have a more pragmatic concern behind such charity towards the smallfolk. Unlike Cersei, Olenna and the Tyrells are aware of the difficulties of ruling a population of angry and starving people.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[Kissed by Fire]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt; While it is self-serving of the Tyrells, it could also be said to be basic good governance, and the smallfolk are getting real benefits from it. While Cersei and Joffrey earned the scorn of the smallfolk for mistreating them, Margaery Tyrell quickly becomes beloved by the smallfolk for easing their suffering.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[And Now His Watch is Ended]]&lt;/ref&gt; At Joffrey and Margaery's [[Purple Wedding|wedding feast]],Â Margaery announces that all the leftover food will be donated to the poor; Cersei secretly countermands the decision.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[The Lion and the Rose]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

sections.Quotes:
{{Dialogue a-b-a|Tyrion Lannister|Listen to me Queen Regent, you're losing the people.  Do you hear me?|Cersei Lannister|The people?  You think I care?|You might find it difficult to rule millions who want you dead.  Half the city will starve when winter comes, the other half will plot to overthrow you.|Cersei's lack of concern about the smallfolk|The Night Lands}}

{{dialogue a-b-c|Varys|The peasants say a long summer means an even longer winter.|Grand Maester Pycelle|A common superstition.|Petyr Baelish|We have enough wheat for a five-year winter.  If it lasts any longer...we'll have fewer peasants.|Littlefinger flippantly explains the Lannisters' strategy for dealing with a protracted winter.|The North Remembers}}

{{Dialogue a-b-a|Davos Seaworth|I understand why the older families look down at me.|Stannis Baratheon|Do you? Why?|My father was a crabber. Sons of lords don't like to break bread with sons of crabbers. Our hands stink.|Davos on the relationship between between high-born lords and low-born smallfolk|The Prince of Winterfell}}

{{Quote|The people are hungry for more than just food. They crave distractions, and if we don't provide them, they'll create their own. And their distractions are likely to end with us being torn to pieces.|Olenna Tyrell to [[Tyrion Lannister]] on the importance of an extravagant royal wedding|Kissed by Fire}}
